ince the transition to democracy, Keller reveals how haunting serves to mourn loss, redefine space and history, and confirm the significance of lives and stories previously hidden or erased. Her richly illustrated book constitutes a significant reevaluation of fascist and post-fascist Spanish visual culture and a unique theorization of haunting as an aesthetic register inextricably connected to the visual and the landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArt and historyxSpain. 0aArt and historyzSpain. 0aHistoriography and photographyxSpain. 0aHistoriography and photographyzSpain. 0aLandscape photographyxHistoryx20th centuryxSpain. 0aLandscape photographyzSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aLoss (Psychology) in art. 0aPhotographyxHistoryx20th centuryxSpain. 0aPhotographyzSpainxHistoryy20th century. 7aART / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066595640uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144261893040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442618930423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442618930.jpg  a978-3-11-066595-6  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles